title: For Sale:  Beretta A 391 Xtrema
postcontent:
Selling for a friend who thought he'd get into duck hunting but now has a little one on the way. Used only a couple times almost brand new paid over $1500 but will sacrifice for $950. Only mark on gun is on sling stud, a new one is $11.00.
The Xtrema was released in mid-2004, to answer the call from hunters and target shooters for a complete do-all shotgun. Beretta’s goal was to produce a shotgun that could reliably fire 2¾” loaded with light target loads all the way through the 3½” super magnum round without any modification or settings to be dealt with. They decided to take the AL391-Xtrema, and update it to fit their needs. They also wanted to add as many recoil reduction features as possible to the shotgun to increase follow-up shot accuracy while target shooting and hunting

The A391 had several features that were designed to increase accuracy and reliability. For one, Beretta decided to strip away as many o-rings and springs as possible for less chance of wear, and also to make easier for the weapon to be field stripped without the accidental loss of parts. They chose to go with a gas-operated action instead of inertia-driven action.
Another advantage is in the over-bored barrel design, which reduces muzzle jump and also improves shot-patterns.
Beretta also redesigned their stock choke system by increasing the length of the choke inside the barrel for a more gradual constriction, without having to add to the length of the barrel like after-market choke tubes do.
They then also chose to take the time-proven technology of hydraulic shock absorption from car-manufactures and put it in the gun’s stock for up to 44% felt recoil reduction at the shoulder.
Beretta also saw the need for the gun to be protected from the elements so as to protect the gun in harsh hunting conditions such as water-fowl hunting, where salt spray can damage a gun within hours. Beretta’s answer to this need was to coat the gun’s working parts in a micro-thin membrane which completely protects the metal (which are not made from stainless steel, chromium, or aluminum) from corrosion while out in the field.
Other improvements include an extra long barrel tang (the part of the barrel that fits into the receiver, and is actually behind the chamber) to more accurately fix the barrel to the receiver in order to increase accuracy when using slugs with a scope fixed to the receiver.
Stock spacers are also available to change the length of pull without major modification.

title: For Sale:  Scammer Warning
postcontent:
Hey all, 

In case you havent noticed, there have been a few scammers out there lately. They are generally trying to sell semi-auto rifles or other high priced items. Here are a few things to look out for or ways to identify a scam:

1) The seller has a live.com email account. At least most of the scammers of interacted with here.
2) Copy and Paste the whole (or part of the) description into google search. The scammers are using bidding sites (like gunbroker) and using the descriptions verbatim. And often using the exact pictures from the bidding site.
3) The lister doesnt seem to know that Maryland just banned the item(s)
4) There are 2 or 3 items like this listed back to back
5) The seller will ask you to wire them money.

If you come across these scams, mark them as such to protect your brothers in arms.

title: For Sale:  STI Sentry 1911 45
postcontent:
Due to some pending changes on the homefront, up for sale is my STI Sentry in 45 ACP. (current retail of $1685.00) As it turns out, the return policy on Marital Bliss does not include a refund. 
I bought it new from the fine folks at Shooters Connection earlier this year. It's awesome. Pure 1911 awesome, inspired by Saint John Moses Browning himself. 

This 1911 is hand fit, the slide to frame fit is every bit as well done as a Brown or a Wilson. The bushing fit is perfect, no binding or stiction, but no slop either. 
It has a number of very nice features: 30LPI checking on the front strap, high cut beavertail grip safety with knuckle relief, and see that beautifully undercut trigger guard? All those features make this a very soft shooting, easily controllable gun. 

In addition to those features from the factory, the magwell has been professionally opened and blended on a mill by the incomparable Allen Moore (Indy area gunsmith who is a wizard on the mill - $100) This makes for speedy, smooth and consistent reloads. The mag glides in like ..well.....use your imagination. The slide also has a nice, conservative bevel on the bottom corners, as you can see in the photo. 

The slide stop has been upgraded to a forged tool steel unit from EGW. The grips are VZ Operators ($70) The factory STI cocobolo grips will be included. You'll also get both an EGW tool steel single sided safety ($60, pictured) and the OEM ambi safety. 

The trigger is currently set at 2.25lbs. You can easily go lighter. You can slap it like Ike slapped Tina and still get great hits. Between the top shelf fitting and the orgasmic trigger, this pistol is extremely accurate. The ignition system has the best of everything. Inifnity triglide trigger with short flat insert. EGW hard sear. Koening hammer, titanium strut and cap, Dawson hyperdrive firing pin. Its got a 21lb mainspring, so it will set off anything, and has about as fast a lock time as a 1911 is going to get. 

It's won me quite a few matches, as well as earned me my USPSA M card and a spot on the Top 20 Sandbagger list in SSTK. 

The gun will come with both the OEM dual springs recoilmaster system, as well as a 1 piece full length guide rod ($30) You'll get the factory mag release button, along with the Dawson Cam-lock extended button shown. Also the factory box, magazine, and bushing wrench. Factory mag as well. 

The gun was cerakoted recently, and looks really, really good. 

There is some wear in the magwell from dryfire practice. There's nothing wrong with the gun aside from that, and frankly I'd rather sell my right nut. Unfortunately, the market for that particular item isn't great, and the package is an absolute pain to split up. 

I'm asking $1500. If you ask what my bottom dollar is, it's $1700. I'm in the Muncie area, and would like to keep it reasonably close. (reasonably close = 30-45 minute drive) I'm willing to ship if you're not a resident of this picturesque area of the country and willing to pay for it. 

When/if gun sells, buyer will have first dibs on 10 Tripp mags, 2 Wilson ETMs, a DAA PDR and/or a Blade-tech holster. Not to be a Richard about it, but I wont be separating those until the gun is sold. Please dont ask. 

TRADES - I'm not really looking for any gun trades at the moment. Cash is King. Small pistol primers, Montana Gold/Zero/Precision delta 9mm jacketed projectiles, and VV N320, N330, N340 or Bullseye powder might be dukes or barons. I get fuzzy on the royal chain of command below princes, but you get the idea.
